      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Power of C + Z Combinations</h2>
      <p>C and Z together form some of Scrabble's most efficient short words. COZ and CUZ both score 14 points in just three letters — that's nearly 5 points per tile, which is exceptional efficiency. These words are especially lethal when you can place the Z on a premium square while the C anchors to an existing word on the board.</p>
      <p>COZY (18 pts) extends this partnership into four letters, and COZILY (20 pts) reaches six letters while maintaining strong point density. If you hold C and Z simultaneously, you're almost guaranteed a high-scoring play.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">C-Word Strategy Tips</h2>
      <p>C is more versatile than it first appears. Here's how to get the most from it:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Know CWM:</strong> This Welsh-origin word (a type of valley) scores 10 points with no vowels. It's a lifesaver when your rack is stacked with consonants and you need to dump tiles without wasting a turn.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>C + K doubles up:</strong> Words ending in -CK (BLOCK, TRACK, QUICK) score well because K is worth 5 points. The CK combination appears in hundreds of valid words.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use C as a back hook:</strong> Many words gain a C at the end — ARC, EPIC, DISC, ZINC. Back-hooking with C creates scoring opportunities from existing board words.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>CH- words are everywhere:</strong> The CH cluster opens up CHALK, CHUNK, CHICK, CHECK, CHARM — common words that reliably score 12-16 points.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Q without U? Think C:</strong> While not directly related, keeping C for -QUE words like CLIQUE and CHEQUE ensures you're ready if Q appears with a U nearby on the board.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Uncommon C-Words Worth Memorising</h2>
      <p>Beyond the obvious, several lesser-known C-words deliver outsized value:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>CALYX</strong> (17 pts) — the outer part of a flower. Uncommon word, rarely challenged, strong scoring.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>CRUX</strong> (13 pts) — the decisive point of an issue. Short, high-value, easy to play.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>CORTEX</strong> (15 pts) — outer layer of the brain. Six letters with strong point density.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>CONVEX</strong> (18 pts) — curved outward. Pairs the common C with the valuable X for a reliable mid-game play.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Managing C on Your Rack</h2>
      <p>C is a solid mid-tier tile. You generally want to play it within two turns of drawing it — holding C doesn't improve over time the way holding a blank or S might. The exception is when you're building toward a known high-value play like COMPLEX or COXCOMB and the board position is developing favourably.</p>
      <p>If you draw both C tiles, prioritise playing one quickly. Two C tiles on your rack significantly reduces flexibility, as CC doesn't appear in many common word patterns. Look for CH, CK, or CR combinations to deploy at least one C efficiently.</p>

